==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr}} {{term|meringue|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|dum}} {{term|meringue||light evening meal|lang=dum}}, derivative of {{etyl|dum}} *{{term||meren|to dip or soak bread|lang=dum}}, from {{etyl|odt}} *{{term||meren|lang=odt}}, from {{proto|Germanic|marjanan|to grind, pound|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|mer-|to rub, pack|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|meringe|lang=gml}} (< {{term|mern||to dip bread in wine|lang=gml}}), {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|merunge|lang=gmh}} (< {{term|meren|mëren|to soak bread in wine or water for dinner|lang=gmh}}), {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|merian||to purify, cleanse, test|lang=ang}}.

Alternate etymology derives {{etyl|odt}} *{{term||meren|lang=odt}} from {{proto|Germanic|marhin|soup of bread and wine or water|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|mark-||merk-|wet|lang=en}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# A mixture consisting of beaten egg whites and sugar which is added to the tops of pies then browned.
#: ''The key to a good [[Baked Alaska]] is the '''meringue''' topping.''
# A shell made of this mixture which serves as the receptacle for fruit, ice cream or sherbet.
#: ''Shirley particularly likes to have [[strawberry]] with her '''meringue'''.''

